[[File:Watkins Books.JPG|thumb|Watkins Books in Cecil Court]]
'''Watkins Books''' is London's oldest esoteric bookshop specializing in [[esotericism]], [[mysticism]], [[occultism]], [[oriental religion]] and [[contemporary spirituality]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.westendextra.com/news/2010/apr/us-film-producer-supplies-magic-save-occult-bookshop |title=US film producer supplies the magic to save occult bookshop |publisher=West End Extra |date=2010-04-02 |accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref> The book store was established by John M. Watkins, a friend of [[Madame Blavatsky]], in 1897 at 26 [[Charing Cross]]. John Watkins had already been selling books via a catalogue which he began publishing in March 1893.<ref>Watkins Review, Issue 24, June 2010</ref> The first biography of [[Aleister Crowley]] recounts a story of Crowley making all of the books in Watkins magically disappear and reappear.<ref>Page 268, 1952 edition of ''The Great Beast'' by John Symonds</ref>
Geoffrey Watkins (1896–1981) owned and managed the store after his father.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.answers.com/topic/geoffrey-watkins |title=Geoffrey Watkins: Information from |publisher=Answers.com |date= |accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref> He was also an author<ref name="Encyclopedia">{{cite encyclopedia | title=Watkins, Geoffrey (1896-1981) | encyclopedia= Encyclopedia of Occultism and Parapsychology | publisher=The Gale Group Inc./[[Encyclopedia.com]] | accessdate=September 30, 2018 | year=2001 | url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1G2-3403804790.html}}</ref> and publisher, with notable books including first publishing [[Carl Gustav Jung]]'s 1925 edition of ''[[Seven Sermons to the Dead|Septem Sermones ad Mortuos]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.philipcoppens.com/jung.html |title=The automatic writings of Jung |publisher=[[Philipcoppens.com]] |date= |accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref>
In 1901, Watkins Books moved to 21 [[Cecil Court]] where it has been continuously trading ever since. It publishes a magazine called the ''Watkins' Mind Body Spirit magazine'', which has featured leading authors from [[mind-body-spirit]] and esoteric fields. Watkins Books has been owned by [[Etan Ilfeld]] since March 2010.<ref name="The Bookseller">{{cite web | url=http://www.thebookseller.com/news/deal-agreed-over-watkins-books.html | title=Deal agreed over Watkins Books | work=[[The Bookseller]] | date=March 15, 2010 | accessdate=September 30, 2018 | author=Gallagher, Victoria }}</ref><ref>Kindred Spirit, Issue 109</ref> Since then, a new website has been launched, and the store regularly hosts book launches and signings. Additionally, the Watkins website has integrated a spiritual map of London that everyone is invited to contribute to. Watkins Books has also published a free Mind Body Spirit app that is available on the iPhone/iPad and Android devices. <ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/app/mind-body-spirit-books-by/id463439169?mt=8 |title=App Store - Mind Body Spirit Books by Watkins |publisher=Itunes.apple.com |date=2012-02-18 |accessdate=2012-03-08}}</ref>
Watkins makes an annual list of "the 100 Most Spiritually Influential Living People," which is published online and in the spring issue of their magazine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.watkinsbooks.com/review/watkins-spiritual-100-list-2012 |title=The Spiritual 100 - Watkins' annual list of the 100 most spiritually influential living people! |publisher=Watkinsbooks.com |date= |accessdate=2012-12-09}}</ref> The three main factors used to compile the list are that the person has to be alive, the person has to have made a unique and spiritual contribution on a global scale, and the person is frequently googled, appears in [[Nielsen Data]] and is actively talked about on the Internet.
